The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, January 13, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Jan. 12: Rising trend in silver continued to remain unabated on the bullion market here today as the metal surged further to close at an all-time high of Rs 10,155 due to thin supply after a steep rally in the global prices. Heavy stockists demand also aided the steep rise in prices, dealers said. Gold, too, firmed up on increased buying activity. Standard gold (99.9 purity) opened steady at Rs 6,315, but recovered to close at Rs 6,335, registering a gain of Rs 20 over the previous close of Rs 6,315.																								 New Delhi, Jan. 12: The last date for e-filing of TDS returns has been extended by six months to March 31 in view of certain administrative difficulties, an official release said.																								 Mumbai, Jan. 12: Indian Hotels Company Ltd, which operates Taj hotels and resorts, has appointed three senior professionals from the hospitality industry to its core management team. The new incumbents are Franz Zeller, Rajiv Kaul and John Gerrard.																								 Mumbai, Jan. 12: Mastek Ltd has posted a sharp drop in its consolidated net profit at Rs 4.09 crore for the second quarter ended December 2003 as against Rs 16.26 crore in the corresponding previous quarter.																								 Mumbai, Jan. 12: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has barred Parasrampuria Plantations Ltd and its concerned officials from dealing in securities and accessing capital markets for five years, a Sebi release said today.
